      <title>Development of a Biodiversity Index for Residential Towns</title>
      <link>https://xp-song.github.io/project/birt/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 03 Jul 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://xp-song.github.io/project/birt/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;In a time of rapid urbanisation, plants and wildlife are exposed to man-made stresses that result in drastic changes to the richness and composition of these communities. Understanding the impacts of the urban environment on biodiversity is becoming increasingly important.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Environmental indices can be useful tools to evaluate the effectiveness of actions aimed at promoting conservation or mitigating the loss of biodiversity. &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/environment/new-biodiversity-impact-assessment-guidelines-introduced-as-part-of-eia-review&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;Environmental impact assessments&lt;/a&gt; are commonly used to measure the impact of new urban developments, and serve to protect biodiversity through legislation. However, these assessments often rely on opportunistic records of species occurrence, collected at geographic scales that tend to be too coarse for spatial planning in cities.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This project aims to develop a probabilistic spatial index of biodiversity, based on an understanding of how landscape components impact four animal groups—birds, butterflies, odonates and amphibians. Remotely sensed (e.g. satellite imagery, LiDAR) and open data sources are used to generalise findings across the wider landscape. The efficacy of various national policy tools (e.g. Green Plot Ratio) in enriching wildlife are also assessed.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The project is funded from 2016–2022 by the Singapore Housing Development Board ($1,286,980), awarded to the National University of Singapore. The lead investigator is Dr. Chong Kwek Yan.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;opportunities&#34;&gt;Opportunities&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We are looking to hire a Research Assistant in 2021, and offer &lt;a href=&#34;https://kwekings.wordpress.com/about-me/about/student-projects-on-offer/&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;student projects&lt;/a&gt; on topics relating to community ecology and remote sensing. We welcome enquiries from motivated students, and would love to hear about your specific interest in our work.&lt;/p&gt;


















